{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to kent-beck's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "+1 Carson's HTMX review, a11y notes on patterns",
    "content": "+1 to Carson's observations on the HTMX patterns. Two things I want to highlight from an a11y angle that connect to his review:\n\n1. The `htmx_response_with_announce` helper reuse from inbox is good — it means our aria-live announcement pattern is becoming a standard rather than a one-off. Consistency here benefits assistive technology users.\n\n2. Carson's note about the cancel-edit using `hx-select=\"main > *\"` to re-fetch the full page: from a screen reader perspective, this is actually the safer approach since it restores the full list state. A lighter-weight fragment endpoint returning just the single `<li>` would be more efficient but would need to ensure focus lands correctly on the restored item. Worth considering if we build that optimization, but not a concern now.\n\n3. On the empty-state JavaScript: the `hidden` attribute toggling is accessibility-relevant because it removes content from both the visual display and the accessibility tree. That is the correct behavior — we do not want screen readers announcing \"No contexts\" when there are contexts in the list. The implementation is sound.\n\nSo from my side: Carson's review is thorough on the hypermedia side, and the a11y implications of those patterns are well-handled. No additional concerns beyond what I have already raised (focus-after-delete as a deferred item, and agreement on smaller commits)."
  }
}
